{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480233"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"28"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/28"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.14,0.06,0.53,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"28"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/28"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"28"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98399"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for an annual health check with no specific concerns. She reports no palpitations, dyspnoea, chest pain, syncope, or neurological symptoms. She has a medical history of hypertension. Her regular medication is ramipril. She is a retired teacher, does not smoke, and drinks minimal alcohol. There has been no recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 92/min and irregular, blood pressure is 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate is 14/min, SpO2 is 98% on room air, and temperature is 36.6\u00b0C. Heart sounds are dual with no added sounds or murmurs, and there are no signs of heart failure. An electrocardiogram shows atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 95/min. She is commenced on metoprolol for rate control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Withhold anticoagulation","Aspirin","Clopidogrel","Dabigatran","Warfarin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAtrial fibrillation confers an increased risk of embolic stroke that should be systematically estimated using a validated, gender-neutral score such as CHA2DS2-VA. People aged 65 to 74 years and those with hypertension accrue points, and most with a score of one or more derive net clinical benefit from oral anticoagulation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect oral anticoagulants (DOACs) are generally preferred to warfarin for non-valvular atrial fibrillation due to similar or superior efficacy, lower intracranial bleeding risk, fewer interactions, and no need for routine monitoring. \u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E is an example, which is suitable provided kidney function is adequate; it reduces stroke risk with favourable safety compared with warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithholding anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate because a person aged 65 to 74 years with hypertension has a CHA2DS2-VA score of two, indicating sufficient stroke risk to warrant anticoagulation unless there is a clear contraindication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide adequate protection against cardioembolic stroke in atrial fibrillation and carries bleeding risk without meaningful benefit for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation, either alone or in combination with aspirin, as it is inferior to anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is effective but is usually reserved when DOACs are unsuitable, such as with significant kidney impairment, mechanical prosthetic valves, or moderate-to-severe rheumatic mitral stenosis, given monitoring and interaction burdens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["People with atrial fibrillation require structured stroke risk assessment and most with non-zero risk benefit from anticoagulation.","Direct oral anticoagulants are preferred over warfarin for non-valvular atrial fibrillation in the absence of contraindications.","Antiplatelet therapy is not adequate for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation."],"references":["Brieger D, Amerena J, Attia J, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and the Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation 2018. Heart, Lung Circ. 2018; 27:1209-66."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"28"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T20:29:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T20:29:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"28"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116401"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading